That's a bug if the input can have 0's. Wait this is a critical error in the original Java code? Let me check: Yes, looking at the Java code's solve method:

for (int i = 1; i < array.length; i++) { ... }

array.length is 1001, so i runs from 1 to 1000. So they are not including the count at index 0.

let's check the Java code again.) Wait, in the Java code:

int countMax = -1;

for (int i = 1; i < array.length; i++) {

    if (countMax < array[i]) countMax = array[i];

} So the initial countMax is -1, which is lower than any possible array[i], since array[i] counts, which are ≥0. So this ensures that the first non-zero element will set countMax to that. But since they skip index 0, even if there's a high count at 0, it won't be counted.
